<br />
<br />except have the game engine from either Arcana of Eye of the Beholder mix with the Mystic Quest engine in order to seamlessly switch between the two engines, as a single game.
<br />
<br />yes i realize EotB and MQ are both SNES games, however i recall Arcana was originally released for NES, iirc, from walk-thrus in Nintendo Power.
<br />
<br />MQ is basically on par with a NES game, just with special effects only doable on the SNES, with slightly improved range of colors.
<br />
<br />meaning cloning it for NES using a high-level compiler will be easy cake.
<br />
<br />also since Arcana was originally a NES game, comparing the NES and SNES arcana carts would lead insight in how to high-level clone the Eye of the Beholder engine which is extremely similar to Arcana to NES.
<br />
<br />since high-level code is easy to combine with other high-level code,
<br />
<br />it will be much easier to recompile these *cloned* engines as a single multiple point of view engine.
<br />
<br />by this i mean you can see Arcana/EotB's view first person in the hud while viewing MQ's 45 degree top/front top-down main screen and vice versa by choosing to swap the HUD behavior and main screen behavior.
<br />
<br />if nBasic won't cut it, and can't find a c compiler for NES, i will be forced to make this an extremely long term project by making my own c compiler for NES based off the LADS 6502 compiler, of which i have the machine coce source for.
<br />
<br />btw i plan to modify the MQ 45 degree top/front top-down method so that you can press a button to align the 90 interval of map rendering from front to either side or rear.

		

