Mystic Quest overworld, town, dungeon, and battle modes for the NES' custom 6502.<br /><br />i have already cloned the various engine components in the past for PC.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">Bregalad wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><span style="font-size: 75%; line-height: normal">- Reverse engineering an existing game gives you hard to undersand without any comment assembly code, NOT ready to use high level code, no matter on what system.</span></div><br /><br />there existed at one point a QuickBasic compiled binary decompiler back to QuickBasic, there also exist Java decompilers,<br /><br />however with both they decompile to equivalent high-level code, but all the variable/class names are enumerated rather than as the originals due to being lost after compile.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">Bregalad wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><span style="font-size: 75%; line-height: normal">- If you want to make a game, you have to use your own game engine for copiright, moral, and pragmatic reasons. Also you cannot just port a console game engine from one system to another, since a console is an embeeded system, unless the game engine was written with that in mind (probably earasing code optimisation).</span></div><br /><br />i never said port, i said clone.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle">Bregalad wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent"><span style="font-size: 75%; line-height: normal">What you say just make absolutely no sense.</span></div>
<br />
<br />you think i am porting machine code directly, or reverse engineering based off the machine code, i am reverse engineering based off the output. using machine code branch maps as a guide. i don't really give a crap what the actual opcodes are, i use the branch map to reverse engineer based on the output what the branches mean in order to get an idea what is going on and in what order on an abstract level.
<br />
<br />cloning means you do it this method, porting means you use the original machine code and tweak the machine code to run on a different processor set.
<br />
<br />
<br />btw i plan on using some Reverse Polish Notation bytecode as the scripting language. (this means very little overhead and ram consumption.)

		

